<subSubSection pageId="1" pageNumber="449" type="nomenclature">
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,686,729,756]" box="[151,686,729,756]" pageId="1" pageNumber="449">
<heading bold="true" box="[151,686,729,756]" fontSize="11" level="1" pageId="1" pageNumber="449" reason="1">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,686,729,756]" pageId="1" pageNumber="449">
The 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Swinhoe" baseAuthorityYear="1901" box="[207,508,729,756]" class="Insecta" family="Arctiidae" genus="Miltochrista" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="449" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="obliquilinea">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[207,508,729,756]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="449">Miltochrista obliquilinea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species-group
</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1437,801,1548]" pageId="1" pageNumber="449">
Members of the 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Swinhoe" baseAuthorityYear="1901" box="[340,514,801,827]" class="Insecta" family="Arctiidae" genus="Miltochrista" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="449" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="obliquilinea">
<emphasis box="[340,514,801,827]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="449">M. obliquilinea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species-group are small moths with yellowish coloration of the body and wings. The sexual dimorphism is well-expressed: males are slightly smaller in size and have a modified forewing venation, subapically concave costa, a characteristic fringe of hair-like androconial scales between the cell apex and the costa, more elongated discal spot, and more strongly zigzagged postmedial line. In the male genitalia, both the distal costal and saccular processes are present (the latter one is reduced in 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Holloway" baseAuthorityYear="2001" box="[856,1005,945,971]" class="Insecta" family="Arctiidae" genus="Miltochrista" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="449" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="areolifera">
<emphasis box="[856,1005,945,971]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="449">M. areolifera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
), the distal membranous lobe of valva is present in most species (absent in 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Holloway" baseAuthorityYear="2001" box="[569,718,981,1007]" class="Insecta" family="Arctiidae" genus="Miltochrista" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="449" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="areolifera">
<emphasis box="[569,718,981,1007]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="449">M. areolifera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authority="Volynkin &amp; Singh &amp; Černý &amp; Kirti &amp; Datta, 2020" authorityName="Volynkin &amp; Singh &amp; Černý &amp; Kirti &amp; Datta" authorityYear="2020" box="[775,893,981,1007]" class="Insecta" family="Arctiidae" genus="Miltochrista" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="449" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="lavides" status="sp. n.">
<emphasis box="[775,893,981,1007]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="449">M. lavides</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[902,967,982,1008]" pageId="1" pageNumber="449">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[902,967,982,1008]" pageId="1" pageNumber="449" rank="species">sp. n.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
), and the vesica bears a bunch of cornuti originating from a heavily sclerotised plate-like base. In the female genitalia, the ductus bursae is membranous, without antrum. The corpus bursae is strongly spinulose, scobinated, bearing a large thick-walled accessory bursae situated posteriorly. Most species lack appendix bursae (present in 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Holloway" baseAuthorityYear="2001" box="[904,1053,1089,1115]" class="Insecta" family="Arctiidae" genus="Miltochrista" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="449" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="areolifera">
<emphasis box="[904,1053,1089,1115]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="449">M. areolifera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
only). In most species, the ductus seminalis originates from the left side of the anterior section of the corpus bursae, but in 
<taxonomicName authority="Volynkin &amp; Singh &amp; Černý &amp; Kirti &amp; Datta, 2020" authorityName="Volynkin &amp; Singh &amp; Černý &amp; Kirti &amp; Datta" authorityYear="2020" box="[1158,1316,1125,1151]" class="Insecta" family="Arctiidae" genus="Miltochrista" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="449" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="stenovalva" status="sp. n.">
<emphasis box="[1158,1316,1125,1151]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="449">M. stenovalva</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1324,1388,1126,1152]" pageId="1" pageNumber="449">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[1324,1388,1126,1152]" pageId="1" pageNumber="449" rank="species">sp. n.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
and 
<taxonomicName authority="Volynkin &amp; Singh &amp; Černý &amp; Kirti &amp; Datta, 2020" authorityName="Volynkin &amp; Singh &amp; Černý &amp; Kirti &amp; Datta" authorityYear="2020" box="[151,268,1161,1187]" class="Insecta" family="Arctiidae" genus="Miltochrista" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="449" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="lavides" status="sp. n.">
<emphasis box="[151,268,1161,1187]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="449">M. lavides</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[275,338,1162,1188]" pageId="1" pageNumber="449">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[275,338,1162,1188]" pageId="1" pageNumber="449" rank="species">sp. n.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
it originates from the accessory bursae.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="1" pageNumber="449" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1437,801,1548]" pageId="1" pageNumber="449">
The species-group is closely related to the 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Walker" baseAuthorityYear="1862" box="[683,827,1198,1224]" class="Insecta" family="Arctiidae" genus="Miltochrista" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="449" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="cuneifera">
<emphasis box="[683,827,1198,1224]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="449">M. cuneifera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species-group (includes 
<taxonomicName authority="(Walker, 1862)" baseAuthorityName="Walker" baseAuthorityYear="1862" box="[1109,1432,1197,1224]" class="Insecta" family="Arctiidae" genus="Miltochrista" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="449" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="cuneifera">
<emphasis box="[1109,1253,1198,1224]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="449">M. cuneifera</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Walker, F." box="[1268,1424,1197,1224]" pageId="1" pageNumber="449" pagination="82 - 145" refId="ref17821" refString="Walker, F. (1862) Catalogue of the Heterocerous Lepidopterous Insects collected at Sarawak, in Borneo, by Mr. A. R. Wallace, with Descriptions of New Species. Journal of the proceedings of the Linnean Society, Zoology, 6, 82 - 145. https: // doi. org / 10.1111 / j. 1096 - 3642.1862. tb 00935. x" type="journal article" year="1862">Walker, 1862</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName authority="(Wileman &amp; South, 1919)" baseAuthorityName="Wileman &amp; South" baseAuthorityYear="1919" box="[151,586,1233,1259]" class="Insecta" family="Arctiidae" genus="Miltochrista" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="449" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="luzonica">
<emphasis box="[151,284,1233,1259]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="449">M. luzonica</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Wileman, A. E. &amp; South, R." box="[300,578,1233,1259]" pageId="1" pageNumber="449" pagination="49 - 51" refId="ref17892" refString="Wileman, A. E. &amp; South, R. (1919) New Species of Lithosiadae from the Philippines. The Entomologist, 52 (670), 49 - 51." type="journal article" year="1919">Wileman &amp; South, 1919</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authority="Volynkin, 2017" authorityName="Volynkin" authorityYear="2017" box="[643,1005,1233,1260]" class="Insecta" family="Arctiidae" genus="Miltochrista" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="449" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="fascicornuta">
<emphasis box="[643,821,1234,1260]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="449">M. fascicornuta</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Volynkin A. V." box="[828,1005,1233,1259]" pageId="1" pageNumber="449" pagination="145 - 150" refId="ref17473" refString="Volynkin A. V. (2017) Description of a new species of Miltochrista Hubner from Vietnam, with eight new combinations (Lepidoptera, Erebidae, Arctiinae). Zootaxa, 4286 (1), 145 - 150. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 4286.1.13" type="journal article" year="2017">Volynkin, 2017</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
), but male genitalia of the 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Swinhoe" baseAuthorityYear="1901" class="Insecta" family="Arctiidae" genus="Miltochrista" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="449" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="obliquilinea">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="449">M. obliquilinea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species-group differ by their well-developed distal costal process (absent in the 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Walker" baseAuthorityYear="1862" box="[1113,1257,1270,1296]" class="Insecta" family="Arctiidae" genus="Miltochrista" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="449" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="cuneifera">
<emphasis box="[1113,1257,1270,1296]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="449">M. cuneifera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species-group), the presence of a bunch of cornuti originating from a heavily sclerotised plate-like base (in the 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Walker" baseAuthorityYear="1862" box="[1237,1381,1306,1332]" class="Insecta" family="Arctiidae" genus="Miltochrista" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="449" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="cuneifera">
<emphasis box="[1237,1381,1306,1332]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="449">M. cuneifera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species-group cornuti are separated from each other and have no broadened base). In female genitalia, the 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Swinhoe" baseAuthorityYear="1901" class="Insecta" family="Arctiidae" genus="Miltochrista" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="449" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="obliquilinea">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="449">M. obliquilinea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species-group differs from the 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Walker" baseAuthorityYear="1862" box="[558,701,1378,1404]" class="Insecta" family="Arctiidae" genus="Miltochrista" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="449" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="cuneifera">
<emphasis box="[558,701,1378,1404]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="449">M. cuneifera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species-group (illustrated by 
<bibRefCitation author="Holloway, J. D." box="[1033,1234,1377,1403]" pageId="1" pageNumber="449" pagination="279 - 486" refId="ref17110" refString="Holloway, J. D. (2001) The Moths of Borneo, part 7. Family Arctiidae, subfamily Lithosiinae. Malayan Nature Journal, 55, 279 - 486." type="journal article" year="2001">Holloway (2001))</bibRefCitation>
by the absence of antrum (that is present in the 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Walker" baseAuthorityYear="1862" box="[482,626,1414,1440]" class="Insecta" family="Arctiidae" genus="Miltochrista" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="449" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="cuneifera">
<emphasis box="[482,626,1414,1440]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="449">M. cuneifera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species-group), the presence of an accessory bursae situated posteriorly (that is absent in the 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Walker" baseAuthorityYear="1862" box="[380,522,1450,1476]" class="Insecta" family="Arctiidae" genus="Miltochrista" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="449" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="cuneifera">
<emphasis box="[380,522,1450,1476]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="449">M. cuneifera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species-group), and the corpus bursae more or less evenly covered with numerous spinules (whereas in the 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Walker" baseAuthorityYear="1862" box="[432,576,1486,1512]" class="Insecta" family="Arctiidae" genus="Miltochrista" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="449" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="cuneifera">
<emphasis box="[432,576,1486,1512]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="449">M. cuneifera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species-group the corpus bursae bears band-like clusters of short but robust denticles only).
</paragraph>
